{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "These datasets are:(1) LDC2014 T12foot_1 (AMR 1.0) [79]: As a starting point, this dataset contains ∼13K English natural language sentences from newswires, weblogs, and web discussion forums.",
    "The ontology used in AMR 1.0 was less detailed and comprehensive compared to later versions.",
    "(2) LDC2017 T10foot_2 (AMR 2.0) [80]: This version provides more precise and consistent guidelines for annotating AMRs, supporting the representation of a wider range of semantic phenomena, such as temporal expressions.",
    "It includes ∼39K English natural language sentences from broadcast conversations, newswire, weblogs, and web discussion forums.",
    "(3) LDC2020 T02foot_3 (AMR 3.0) [51]: This is the most comprehensive, with the largest number of sentences and the most refined and consistent annotations."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "These datasets are:(1) LDC2014 T12foot_1 (AMR 1.0) [79]: As a starting point, this dataset contains ∼13K English natural language sentences from newswires, weblogs, and web discussion forums.",
    "(2) LDC2017 T10foot_2 (AMR 2.0) [80]: This version provides more precise and consistent guidelines for annotating AMRs, supporting the representation of a wider range of semantic phenomena, such as temporal expressions.",
    "(3) LDC2020 T02foot_3 (AMR 3.0) [51]: This is the most comprehensive, with the largest number of sentences and the most refined and consistent annotations."
  ]
